The new Walther SOFTCOIL ™ gas-delayed blowback technology works to make the CCP an excellent concealed carry firearm. How Walther SOFTCOIL ™ Technology Makes This Pistol A Must-Have The CCP’s SOFTCOIL™ gas-delayed blowback system uses gas pressure from the ignited cartridge by directing it through a small port in the barrel in front of the chamber to slow down and delay the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined after the bullet has left the barrel. This allows the slide to end its rearward motion, opening the breech, and ejecting the empty cartridge case. Benefits of Walther SOFTCOIL ™ Technology 1. It allows the slide to be easily manipulated to chamber a round. 2. Barrel rise is reduced up to one third less than similar pistols. 3. Decrease barrel rise helps you remain focused to accurately hit your target shot after shot. Size & Features With an overall length of just 6.41 inches, the Walther CCP is a sleek solution to concealed carry protection. The new model’s barrel length is 3.54 inches and its width is only 1.18 inches making it easily carried in a purse or inside-the-pant holster. The CCP comes in stylish stainless or Cerakote® black and provides all the features that have become a signature of Walther’s line of pistols. It has a smooth 5.5 pound trigger pull, interchangeable front sight with white dot, adjustable rear sight, and reversible magazine release for left- or right-handed operation. This new single-stack semi-automatic has a magazine capacity of 8 rounds. For maximum safety, the CCP comes equipped with a slim manual thumb safety and one internal safety that acts as a firing pin block. As with all Walther firearms, the CCP has an ergonomic grip with a unique non-slip surface. Other key attributes of the firearm include an easy access slide stop, loaded chamber indicator for added safety, and serrations (front, rear and trigger guard) for additional safety and control of its easily manipulated slide.

The 725 receiver is significantly lower than other Citori 12 gauge receivers, yet the 725 shares the renowned durability of generations of Citori over-and-unders with the same rugged full-width hinge pin and tapered locking bolt design. The features don't stop there-the 725 showcases the FireLite mechanical trigger that offers unmatched feel and lighter pull weights than ever before. Inflex Technology has also been added to make shooting more comfortable and the Invector-DS choke system moves the gun to a new level of performance. The Field model features a gloss-oil-finished, checkered grade II/III walnut stock and an engraved low-profile steel receiver. A set of three Invector-DS choke tubes are included.

title: For Sale:  Federal Practice and Defense Ammo .45acp
postcontent:
Train Like You're Going to Fight.
If you practice with "Managed Recoil" loads, what's going to happen when you have to shoot those full power hollow points you carry? Will you be surprised by the recoil? You might not be holding the pistol tightly enough. 

Then again, you don't want to dump money into the backstop at the range by shooting hollow points for practice either. 

I have a single sealed box of 120 rounds of Federal .45 ACP ammo. It really is an ingenious concept. If you've just bought a .45 and need to practice with it before it becomes your CCW gun, this is a perfect deal. If you just want some practice ammunition and some jacketed hollow point ammo for defense, it's a good deal, too. Otherwise you could buy this one box and add to your overall supply of practice and defense ammo.

The price was $65, which is Midway's price before shipping. I have lowered it to $55 as aguideline. I'll take the best offer that puts cash In My Hand by Tuesday. I have another deal in the works and have to pay the guy on Tuesday.

Both the practice ammo and the defense ammo are 230 grain bullets, so theoretically, you'll have the same recoil, muzzle flip and recovery in practice as you will get if you ever have to fire the Hydra-Shok defense ammo, when your life may depend on that second or third round.

title: For Sale:  Taurus PT 96AF with three magazines
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
I am only selling this to fund another purchase. It has been dead reliable and accurate, and there are no problems with it. This is an early one (probably the mid-1980s) and was a high tech, high quality pistol in its day. 

I assume you already know that this Taurus was made on Beretta machinery left over after Beretta fulfilled a military contract with Brazil. I actually prefer it to the Beretta since this one can be carried cocked and locked like a 1911. Frame mounted safety feels better to me and is quicker than the slide mounted one on a Beretta too. Of course since it is a double action, you really don't even need to use the safety to carry it.

It comes with three magazines and all function fine. Features orange three dot sights. I have never had a malfunction of any kind with it, and I would trust my life to it.

Overall it is as reliable as any Beretta, and for the money I don't think you can beat it. I am firm on this price (lol, it's cheap) and I don't think you can find a better value in a serious self defense handgun. Period.

I am in Santa Fe and can meet you almost any time. Contact me through Armslist with your phone number and I will call you so we can meet up.
